145
00:07:29,733 --> 00:07:33,777
So with an authored level, you know, right at the beginning you're getting your mechanics going and all that and that's cool.

146
00:07:34,097 --> 00:07:37,640
And you can knock out some white box levels, test out some stuff and that's cool.

147
00:07:37,980 --> 00:07:43,225
And then for the life of the project, you're forever working on the levels, making new ones, generating content for your game.

148
00:07:44,065 --> 00:07:46,466
With procedural levels, it's a bit different because

149
00:07:47,267 --> 00:07:50,408
although in the back-end you don't have to do all that creation, up front

150
00:07:50,908 --> 00:07:53,389
you can't do anything until you have the system working.

151
00:07:53,409 --> 00:07:56,930
You gotta sit down with the programmer and figure out how this thing's gonna work,

152
00:07:57,270 --> 00:07:59,811
how you're gonna edit it, what you might need to do in the future,

153
00:07:59,871 --> 00:08:01,092
how it's gonna be extensible.

154
00:08:01,572 --> 00:08:03,653
So it takes a bunch of extra time up front.

155
00:08:04,053 --> 00:08:06,974
But then on the back-end, you know, the workload gets a lot lower.

156
00:08:07,374 --> 00:08:09,775
It doesn't go all the way down to zero, just like any design.

157
00:08:09,815 --> 00:08:12,516
It needs to be iterated on and refined and improved.

158
00:08:13,541 --> 00:08:17,066
But yeah, so that was kind of my feeling about doing procedural level generation.

159
00:08:17,507 --> 00:08:19,570
So we had all these different entities we wanted to place.

160
00:08:19,670 --> 00:08:21,853
Zappers, coins, lasers, all kinds of stuff.

161
00:08:22,744 --> 00:08:24,865
And we came up with this idea of the interval system.

162
00:08:25,646 --> 00:08:28,408
This is extremely basic, this is not rocket science by any means.

163
00:08:28,508 --> 00:08:31,109
Basically, the game comes up with a whole set of intervals,

164
00:08:31,409 --> 00:08:33,631
you know, down the corridor that Barry runs down,

165
00:08:34,171 --> 00:08:39,394
and every type of entity has the probability of falling into the next slot.

166
00:08:39,414 --> 00:08:42,196
So it's like a 50% chance it'll be a zapper,

167
00:08:42,476 --> 00:08:44,457
50% or, sorry, 20% chance it'll be coins,

168
00:08:44,877 --> 00:08:46,038
20% chance it'll be missiles,

169
00:08:46,358 --> 00:08:48,360
and 10% chance it'll be something else.

170
00:08:49,420 --> 00:08:51,441
So you know, this is all pretty simple stuff.

171
00:08:52,832 --> 00:08:55,476
So then the problem was figuring out, you know,

172
00:08:56,096 --> 00:08:57,238
where to put these intervals.

173
00:08:57,498 --> 00:08:58,980
By the way, if you're looking at this screen

174
00:08:59,100 --> 00:09:00,862
and for some reason, and you don't know why,

175
00:09:00,922 --> 00:09:02,224
your fingers are cramping up,

176
00:09:03,386 --> 00:09:06,149
it's because I was looking for an athletics track

177
00:09:06,189 --> 00:09:08,772
and I just completely stole the background out of QWOP.

178
00:09:11,338 --> 00:09:16,502
So a regular interval system, you know, you see, it's there, it's reliable, but it's boring.

179
00:09:17,202 --> 00:09:21,245
So if we randomize it a bit and have totally random intervals, then that's cool,

180
00:09:21,966 --> 00:09:24,608
but total random is crazy, right?

181
00:09:25,309 --> 00:09:28,271
It's really hard to keep track of what's happening in a total random system,

182
00:09:28,331 --> 00:09:30,132
and maybe it works fine, like 90% of the time.

183
00:09:31,149 --> 00:09:33,630
But then every now and then you'll have that outlier where

184
00:09:33,830 --> 00:09:37,232
you have this massive gap and nothing happens and there's no gates and then, you know,

185
00:09:37,572 --> 00:09:41,414
all of a sudden there's like three gates right on top of each other and, you know, that's no good.

186
00:09:42,154 --> 00:09:46,596
So our solution is pretty basic. It's basically, you know, you have a minimum interval length,

187
00:09:46,716 --> 00:09:49,277
a maximum interval length and you randomize inside that.

188
00:09:50,478 --> 00:09:54,220
Again, there's nothing all that exciting about that, but what's really, really good about this system

189
00:09:54,280 --> 00:09:58,121
for, you know, randomizing and, you know, doing procedural level generation

190
00:09:58,201 --> 00:09:59,862
is how easy it is to change.

191
00:10:00,990 --> 00:10:05,313
you can really easily modify that minimum interval length and maximum interval length

192
00:10:05,833 --> 00:10:08,154
and in doing so you dramatically change

193
00:10:08,775 --> 00:10:09,835
the difficulty of the game.

194
00:10:10,956 --> 00:10:14,638
Monster Dash, when we had that, that just got faster and faster and faster forever

195
00:10:15,279 --> 00:10:18,921
and the problem was, at a point you were just jumping blindly and just

196
00:10:19,001 --> 00:10:22,763
hoping you would make it over stuff. It got so fast that there's no way you could

197
00:10:22,843 --> 00:10:23,603
actually react.

198
00:10:24,595 --> 00:10:27,396
By using this system, we were able to do it a bit smarter.

199
00:10:27,416 --> 00:10:29,957
You speed up at the beginning, and then your speed

200
00:10:29,997 --> 00:10:30,698
stays constant.

201
00:10:30,718 --> 00:10:32,318
And we start messing with these numbers.

202
00:10:32,338 --> 00:10:35,319
We start bringing the minimum, maximum interval lengths down.

203
00:10:35,799 --> 00:10:38,000
And that brings everything closer together

204
00:10:38,080 --> 00:10:40,541
and requires the player to have more accuracy when

205
00:10:40,601 --> 00:10:41,662
flying between obstacles.

206
00:10:43,499 --> 00:10:47,321
So the minimum interval is what's really interesting in this MinMax system,

207
00:10:47,362 --> 00:10:51,425
because the minimum intervals kind of represents what's unfair about the game.

208
00:10:52,666 --> 00:10:55,528
So in Monster Dash we had these enemies, the zombies are a good one,

209
00:10:55,568 --> 00:10:57,790
where they just pop out right in front of you, right?

210
00:10:58,190 --> 00:11:01,533
And where they can pop out in front of you is measured in distance from Barry,

211
00:11:02,453 --> 00:11:04,075
and there's a minimum and a maximum value.

212
00:11:05,188 --> 00:11:09,810
And the minimum value is really deciding how unfair this system is, right?

213
00:11:09,830 --> 00:11:12,731
So here's some more scientific graphs, as you'll see.

214
00:11:14,091 --> 00:11:17,132
I'm all about really carefully researched data, you can tell.

215
00:11:18,113 --> 00:11:19,913
And this is the player reaction-o-meter.

216
00:11:20,433 --> 00:11:23,414
And obviously, if this zombie appears right in front of your nose,

217
00:11:23,695 --> 00:11:25,395
the player's just gonna be like, well, fuck this game.

218
00:11:25,635 --> 00:11:27,136
You know, screw this. This is impossible.

219
00:11:27,576 --> 00:11:29,077
This game is treating me unfairly.

220
00:11:29,557 --> 00:11:30,637
I want to have nothing to do with it.

221
00:11:31,017 --> 00:11:33,498
slide it along a bit and you know it'll still be impossible,

222
00:11:34,138 --> 00:11:37,439
but then you're gonna start getting this point where it's gonna get a bit blurry

223
00:11:37,720 --> 00:11:40,561
and they're gonna be like, well maybe if I was just a little bit faster,

224
00:11:40,821 --> 00:11:43,962
just a little bit quicker off the mark, then I could have gotten it.

225
00:11:44,642 --> 00:11:48,383
And a little bit past that, you know, where they actually get it at the very last moment,

226
00:11:48,423 --> 00:11:51,864
that's your crazy oh shit moment, which you know, the player feels really good about.

227
00:11:52,465 --> 00:11:56,666
So really where this minimum interval is set is deciding how unfair the game is.

228
00:11:58,106 --> 00:11:58,207
And...

