00:36:52,162 --> 00:36:55,184
or whether it should all stay within the same shop area.

685
00:36:56,845 --> 00:36:59,466
So again, yeah, it's looking alright, but still not quite happy with it.

686
00:36:59,586 --> 00:37:02,888
There's a lot of text on that screen, right? There's a lot going on.

687
00:37:03,888 --> 00:37:04,949
So we tried kind of...

688
00:37:05,958 --> 00:37:09,859
horizontalifying the whole thing, like getting rid of the noise down the sides.

689
00:37:09,879 --> 00:37:14,380
So you can see it's kind of been stretched out and you can kind of see this is starting to get close to the

690
00:37:14,720 --> 00:37:16,121
current shop implementation.

691
00:37:17,001 --> 00:37:20,382
We still have the two categories, the for sale and the my stuff, so you know the

692
00:37:20,462 --> 00:37:23,283
inventory and stuff I haven't yet bought. We've got down the bottom

693
00:37:24,203 --> 00:37:26,944
the uh... you know a lot of Apple apps have the

694
00:37:27,204 --> 00:37:30,445
categories listed down that way in those black bars but

695
00:37:31,165 --> 00:37:32,245
you know and then eventually

696
00:37:33,039 --> 00:37:36,021
we came up with the idea that we would pull all the categories out to the top

697
00:37:36,061 --> 00:37:38,903
level and that way we could have visuals and again give it a bit of character

698
00:37:39,564 --> 00:37:40,405
and then finally the

699
00:37:40,825 --> 00:37:41,826
the end result there

700
00:37:43,087 --> 00:37:46,289
it obviously looks much better because at this point then an artist touched it

701
00:37:47,290 --> 00:37:51,032
you can see that you know design-wise that was kind of the next obvious step

702
00:37:51,873 --> 00:37:55,035
and you can see how similar that is to the app store right like you even got

703
00:37:55,055 --> 00:37:58,258
the glossy icons and everything the biggest change more than anything

704
00:37:58,698 --> 00:38:01,540
is that when you click an item rather than pushing you to a whole new page it

705
00:38:01,580 --> 00:38:02,461
just kinda pops down

706
00:38:05,037 --> 00:38:06,058
Okay, so that's the shop.

707
00:38:07,019 --> 00:38:08,340
Next thing, mission system.

708
00:38:10,521 --> 00:38:14,684
So the mission system was originally inspired by the little system in Tiny Wings.

709
00:38:15,025 --> 00:38:18,707
I thought that was a really neat idea when I was playing it, but I had a lot of problems with it too.

710
00:38:19,168 --> 00:38:22,770
I wanted to do kind of more reward structures and, you know, more interesting stuff.

711
00:38:22,790 --> 00:38:26,593
It felt cool completing missions, but I never really felt fulfilled by doing so.

712
00:38:27,253 --> 00:38:33,978
And I would often get stuck on a mission and, you know, really sit there tearing my hair out trying to get past it.

713
00:38:35,001 --> 00:38:37,384
So we figured we'll budget one week to do this thing.

714
00:38:38,586 --> 00:38:42,491
If you assume that like four weeks was accurate to make this game in nine months,

715
00:38:42,711 --> 00:38:44,754
then this one week estimate is pretty close.

716
00:38:47,640 --> 00:38:53,343
So we tried three different things in addressing these, you know, in improving this mission system.

717
00:38:53,803 --> 00:38:57,185
We had the daily system, the optional system, and the progressive system.

718
00:38:57,906 --> 00:38:59,847
So the daily system was our first one.

719
00:38:59,927 --> 00:39:00,727
The idea is this.

720
00:39:01,327 --> 00:39:03,648
Every single day you get three new missions you can do.

721
00:39:03,709 --> 00:39:06,690
There's an easy mission, a medium mission, and a hard mission.

722
00:39:07,410 --> 00:39:11,253
That way I know I'm never going to get stuck because you know I've always got an easy mission to do there

723
00:39:11,413 --> 00:39:14,976
and when you complete the easy mission it's just it's done. That's it for the day.

724
00:39:14,996 --> 00:39:18,638
You don't get another one to replace it. It's just there and then I check back tomorrow.

725
00:39:19,565 --> 00:39:20,906
and I'll have three new missions to do.

726
00:39:21,626 --> 00:39:23,228
And that seemed like a really cool idea,

727
00:39:23,748 --> 00:39:25,450
you know, on the surface of it, because we know

728
00:39:25,510 --> 00:39:27,651
it's going to address the problem, no one's going to get stuck,

729
00:39:27,792 --> 00:39:29,473
clearly, like, even if you can't even complete

730
00:39:29,533 --> 00:39:31,575
the easy mission, then you can just

731
00:39:31,615 --> 00:39:33,616
come back the next day and, you know, maybe you'll be able to complete

732
00:39:33,636 --> 00:39:35,538
the next one. Our goal of

733
00:39:35,578 --> 00:39:37,620
making it sticky, this seemed like a cool idea

734
00:39:37,680 --> 00:39:39,561
because, you know, you'd be able to

735
00:39:39,601 --> 00:39:41,563
keep coming back, there'd be incentive to come back

736
00:39:41,623 --> 00:39:43,405
every single day, so it seemed kind of neat.

737
00:39:44,125 --> 00:39:45,586
And we did another

738
00:39:45,626 --> 00:39:47,488
kind of company beta and one third of the

739
00:39:47,528 --> 00:39:48,649
company got this system.

740
00:39:50,780 --> 00:39:53,062
The second system we did was this optional system.

741
00:39:53,362 --> 00:39:55,023
So again, really trying to address the issue

742
00:39:55,063 --> 00:39:55,764
of getting stuck.

743
00:39:56,625 --> 00:39:57,345
So this was simple.

744
00:39:57,545 --> 00:40:00,227
At all times, you basically had two missions to complete.

745
00:40:00,307 --> 00:40:02,669
And rather than it being one and the other,

746
00:40:02,909 --> 00:40:03,970
it was one or the other.

747
00:40:03,990 --> 00:40:06,111
So this one, run 800 meters in a little stomper

748
00:40:06,131 --> 00:40:08,934
in a single run, or spend a total of 2,000 coins.

749
00:40:08,974 --> 00:40:12,096
And you'll notice the top one is a skill-based mission.

750
00:40:12,196 --> 00:40:15,198
The bottom one is this kind of grind, time-based mission.

751
00:40:15,238 --> 00:40:17,520
Something that anyone could do given enough time.

752
00:40:17,980 --> 00:40:19,821
Experienced players are gonna complete it quicker.

753
00:40:20,804 --> 00:40:24,245
But, you know, anyone will get there if they invest enough time into it.

754
00:40:24,886 --> 00:40:28,007
So this was the second mission we tried and, you know, we put that one over there and,

755
00:40:28,487 --> 00:40:30,768
you know, again it's kind of neat but

756
00:40:31,848 --> 00:40:33,049
it's feeling a little bit off.

757
00:40:34,429 --> 00:40:38,170
The final one is the progressive system. So this is obviously the one closest to

758
00:40:38,350 --> 00:40:39,991
the current system as we know it in the game.

759
00:40:41,682 --> 00:40:44,265
three missions, you know, you complete one, you get a new one.

760
00:40:45,086 --> 00:40:47,389
We had experience points at this point as well.

761
00:40:48,210 --> 00:40:51,814
And so, you know, this was the system and it was easily the favorite of our playtests.

762
00:40:52,095 --> 00:40:53,577
Again, one third of the company got this.

763
00:40:54,258 --> 00:40:57,942
The problem was with the daily system was the guys who started playing it, like, on a Monday

764
00:40:58,022 --> 00:40:59,845
compared to the guys who started playing it on a Friday.

765
00:41:00,342 --> 00:41:03,867
The guys on Friday felt like no matter what they did, they could never catch up, right?

766
00:41:03,888 --> 00:41:07,172
Because it didn't matter how much time they put into it, they could never catch up to their friends

767
00:41:07,192 --> 00:41:08,334
and they're always one step behind.

768
00:41:08,354 --> 00:41:12,841
And they felt quite disempowered by not having control over what they were able to complete

769
00:41:13,141 --> 00:41:15,244
and how much time they were able to invest in the game.

770
00:41:16,065 --> 00:41:20,388
The optional system worked out a bit better, it seemed okay, but you know,

771
00:41:21,129 --> 00:41:26,152
it kind of delivered the missions in such a, you needed such a long string of them,

772
00:41:26,553 --> 00:41:29,635
and because you were only doing one at a time, it felt really kind of steppy,

773
00:41:29,695 --> 00:41:31,196
and this, and then this, and then this.

774
00:41:31,716 --> 00:41:34,238
Progressive system was easily the favorite for the playtesters,

775
00:41:34,258 --> 00:41:37,340
because they really enjoyed completing multiple missions at once,

776
00:41:37,460 --> 00:41:38,721
and all that kind of stuff.

777
00:41:40,382 --> 00:41:42,664
Originally, we had this rewards system,

778
00:41:43,244 --> 00:41:44,926
which is literally the money-old box.

779
00:41:46,279 --> 00:41:47,980
So when you leveled up, this is what happened.

780
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:49,821
You got this screen and you could either get the money

781
00:41:49,941 --> 00:41:51,782
or you could have what's in this box.

782
00:41:51,842 --> 00:41:54,204
And we had this big list of prizes you could get in the box.

783
00:41:54,264 --> 00:41:55,705
It would unlock things in the shop.

784
00:41:56,025 --> 00:41:57,406
You get random currency rewards.

785
00:41:57,426 --> 00:42:00,688
You might like win $1 instead of taking the easy two grand

786
00:42:00,728 --> 00:42:02,409
or you might win 100,000 coins.

787
00:42:02,929 --> 00:42:05,411
We even had these collectible things that you could get.

788
00:42:05,431 --> 00:42:07,952
They were, you know, we had made some crazy,

789
00:42:08,052 --> 00:42:09,933
stupid large amount of them and they did nothing.

790
00:42:09,973 --> 00:42:11,234
They had no utility value.

791
00:42:11,254 --> 00:42:14,196
It was like a kind of collectible card mini game on the side.

792
00:42:15,430 --> 00:42:19,252
The big problem here was, you know, in the progressive system, people felt like they

793
00:42:19,292 --> 00:42:23,073
wanted the missions to get harder and harder and harder, and because of this reward system,

794
00:42:23,514 --> 00:42:25,755
we weren't able to give bigger rewards.

795
00:42:26,175 --> 00:42:30,317
Because you know, we would ratchet up the money on the money side, but the box is still

796
00:42:30,377 --> 00:42:32,018
always this random kind of box.

797
00:42:32,278 --> 00:42:36,300
And maybe we give them a bigger box, or a golden box, but even still, it was way more

798
00:42:36,340 --> 00:42:41,262
difficult to actually ratchet up the rewards to meet, you know, the expected reward for

799
00:42:41,322 --> 00:42:44,824
more difficult missions, which you would expect as you kind of progress through a system.

800
00:42:47,350 --> 00:42:50,571
So, you know, we had experience points, you know, the bars filling up were nice.

801
00:42:50,611 --> 00:42:54,312
We really wanted, you know, the utility side of things was all good.

802
00:42:54,552 --> 00:42:57,253
We really wanted to make it more punchy and more visceral.

803
00:42:57,333 --> 00:43:02,135
And so, you know, all of the stars that we have, you know, they slam into place.

804
00:43:02,395 --> 00:43:04,455
The whole screen kind of moves around.

805
00:43:04,495 --> 00:43:07,036
I think we even have dust that comes off the stars.

806
00:43:07,056 --> 00:43:08,357
We really put a bit of time into it.

807
00:43:08,757 --> 00:43:13,218
It was able to simplify the experience point system as well to just one, two, and three stars.

808
00:43:15,827 --> 00:43:19,629
And the mission system becomes this crazy surprise mega feature.

809
00:43:19,649 --> 00:43:23,651
Like, honestly, when we started working on it, we were expecting it just to be this thing.

810
00:43:23,691 --> 00:43:25,472
You know, again, one week on the side.

811
00:43:25,512 --> 00:43:29,493
We ended up pouring, I think we spent three months on it.

812
00:43:29,513 --> 00:43:31,714
It took us about a month and a half to get the system right.

813
00:43:31,835 --> 00:43:35,836
And it spent a month and a half of purely just tweaking the order of the missions,

814
00:43:35,876 --> 00:43:38,758
the difficulty of the missions, the variety, coming up with new ones,

815
00:43:39,338 --> 00:43:40,839
cutting the ones that weren't very good.

816
00:43:42,666 --> 00:43:46,069
And now, like, the game is getting crazy addictive, right?

817
00:43:46,469 --> 00:43:48,470
Because we've got so many layers of goals.

818
00:43:48,530 --> 00:43:50,332
You've got, like, the kind of social goals

819
00:43:50,412 --> 00:43:51,713
of trying to beat your friends.

820
00:43:51,733 --> 00:43:54,035
We've got that whole thing going on, like Fruit Ninja.

821
00:43:54,495 --> 00:43:56,937
You've kind of got this status thing of leveling up.

822
00:43:56,957 --> 00:43:57,837
You know, what level are you?

823
00:43:57,938 --> 00:44:00,560
I'm level 463 kind of thing.

824
00:44:00,580 --> 00:44:01,941
So you've got that side of things.

825
00:44:02,341 --> 00:44:05,023
You've got these personal goals of unlocking the stuff

826
00:44:05,063 --> 00:44:06,784
that you like the look of in the shop.

827
00:44:07,621 --> 00:44:11,904
you've got this progressive system, you're working your way through towards an end goal

828
00:44:12,585 --> 00:44:17,248
you know, the game has got so many layers of feedback and reward for the player

829
00:44:17,268 --> 00:44:19,991
that I really think that's what grabs people in and keeps them in

830
00:44:20,291 --> 00:44:23,453
no matter where you are, you're always like, you know, a couple of steps away from the

831
00:44:23,493 --> 00:44:25,335
next awesome thing that's going to happen to you

832
00:44:28,488 --> 00:44:30,749
So we did the mission system and that seemed awesome.

833
00:44:31,070 --> 00:44:33,832
At this point we're like, okay, what about our really hardcore players?

834
00:44:33,872 --> 00:44:36,113
These guys are going to play it, finish it, what are we going to give to them?

835
00:44:36,433 --> 00:44:39,515
So again, you know, we got a bit of inspiration from our Call of Duty.

836
00:44:40,356 --> 00:44:42,357
You know, thought we'd come up with a prestiging system.

837
00:44:42,838 --> 00:44:45,259
But instead of being just ten medals,

838
00:44:45,600 --> 00:44:48,241
we would make these medals and they'd be made out of three components.

839
00:44:48,261 --> 00:44:51,484
They would have five borders, five different fills and five different icons.

840
00:44:51,904 --> 00:44:55,206
That gives us a hundred and twenty-five different badges we can give them instead.

841
00:44:56,177 --> 00:44:57,677
honest to God, when we were working on it,

842
00:44:58,437 --> 00:45:00,778
we were expecting only the hardest of the hardcore

843
00:45:00,818 --> 00:45:03,759
would get a couple of badges, you know, a couple of badges at most.

844
00:45:04,200 --> 00:45:07,361
We put these ID tags on them and gave them all these unique games

845
00:45:07,381 --> 00:45:10,302
because we thought it would give the community this kind of fun game

846
00:45:10,742 --> 00:45:12,543
where they would all try and come together and they'd say,

847
00:45:12,563 --> 00:45:14,763
like, oh, I got badge 63 and I got badge 67,

848
00:45:15,444 --> 00:45:17,504
and a large number of people would come together

849
00:45:17,864 --> 00:45:19,485
to build the definitive list.

850
00:45:20,565 --> 00:45:21,666
So imagine my surprise.

851
00:45:22,934 --> 00:45:27,188
when this gets emailed to me after only 20 days of the game being out.

852
00:45:28,654 --> 00:45:32,256
all 125 medals unlocked by a single person

853
00:45:32,837 --> 00:45:36,159
averaging 8 hours of play everyday, 7 days a week

854
00:45:36,619 --> 00:45:37,520
uh... what do we got there?

855
00:45:37,880 --> 00:45:41,603
I can't see the time that was on there. This is a guy off the Touch Arcade forum

856
00:45:41,623 --> 00:45:42,844
it's called Microbite

857
00:45:43,464 --> 00:45:45,786
and we were just blown away and the crazy thing is is

858
00:45:46,286 --> 00:45:49,609
I mean you know obviously this guy is the extreme case but even casual plays

859
00:45:49,629 --> 00:45:51,970
like even my partner who is definitely not a gamer

860
00:45:52,371 --> 00:45:55,493
comes up to me and is like yeah I got my third medal. I'm like holy shit

861
00:45:56,093 --> 00:45:59,254
three medals, like we were expecting that would be our hardcore players.

862
00:46:00,995 --> 00:46:03,355
The level of engagement in Jetpack is just

863
00:46:04,176 --> 00:46:07,617
off the chains, like you know, we did a lot, you know, that was our goal

864
00:46:08,097 --> 00:46:10,778
for sure, but there's no way we could have anticipated

865
00:46:11,338 --> 00:46:15,059
how high the level of engagement was. Certainly it's got a small audience, I've

866
00:46:15,099 --> 00:46:18,900
added a little question mark there because I wrote all this pre the game going free.

867
00:46:19,720 --> 00:46:21,260
But you know, our engagement is just

868
00:46:21,861 --> 00:46:23,081
out of control for this game.

869
00:46:25,409 --> 00:46:28,134
So, I've got a couple of quick things I'll go over pretty quickly.

870
00:46:28,174 --> 00:46:30,358
Getting this game out the door was terrible.

871
00:46:30,879 --> 00:46:32,221
Terrible, horrible experience.

872
00:46:33,858 --> 00:46:38,860
really, really wanted to make this game work at 60 frames per second on everything.

873
00:46:39,300 --> 00:46:44,641
And like this iPhone made out of clay is probably about as fast as like the original 2G iPhone.

874
00:46:45,321 --> 00:46:50,983
On top of that, we really wanted it to look good on retina display screens as well as iPad 2 and all of that,

875
00:46:51,003 --> 00:46:52,603
which is obviously a major challenge.

876
00:46:52,983 --> 00:46:56,124
But then as if that wasn't enough, we're trying to keep it under 20 megs.

877
00:46:56,964 --> 00:47:02,045
You know, we're really trying to have it all and that was an obvious source of problems for us.

878
00:47:03,012 --> 00:47:06,213
Came up with this kind of neat solution where, I hope that shows up alright,

879
00:47:07,134 --> 00:47:10,995
you know, we really wanted to make it really sparkle and look good on the iPad

880
00:47:11,015 --> 00:47:16,297
but there's no way we could, you know, jam in these sprites that would take up four times more room

881
00:47:16,597 --> 00:47:18,158
to accommodate for Retina and iPad.

882
00:47:18,602 --> 00:47:24,206
So one of the guys at Halfrick actually wrote this kind of custom, it's almost like a HQ2X

883
00:47:24,387 --> 00:47:24,847
scaler.

884
00:47:25,407 --> 00:47:28,750
And so what happens is if you have a retina phone and you boot up Jetpack for the first

885
00:47:28,790 --> 00:47:32,453
time, he goes, I see that you have a retina phone and it takes a little bit longer to

886
00:47:32,493 --> 00:47:36,757
load, it actually goes through and converts a big list of sprites into these, you know,

887
00:47:36,997 --> 00:47:41,381
expanded sprites that aren't nearest neighbor, aren't bilinear because, you know, nearest

888
00:47:41,421 --> 00:47:43,923
neighbor makes it look pixely, which is fine, it's part of the style.

889
00:47:44,504 --> 00:47:50,066
and bilinear makes it look blurry, but this way we kind of get, it looks nice and chunky and smooth and still kind of pixel-y.

890
00:47:50,586 --> 00:47:53,768
So that was a really big breakthrough for us, because it could look great on everything,

891
00:47:54,488 --> 00:48:01,031
but also, you know, it could, it would still fit into 20 megs, because we only had to have these low sprites in there.

892
00:48:01,051 --> 00:48:03,773
We were extremely fortunate that our artist, Sierra,

893
00:48:04,313 --> 00:48:08,138
had been, you know, he's a pixel ninja kind of guy and even though there was absolutely

894
00:48:08,198 --> 00:48:12,523
no, at the time, technical reason he had to, he kept all the sprites, like either eight

895
00:48:12,603 --> 00:48:16,287
or sixteen colors, just because he wanted to, just because he felt like, you know, that

896
00:48:16,307 --> 00:48:17,469
was the way this game should look.

897
00:48:18,010 --> 00:48:22,375
And thank God he did because it meant this, uh, this scaler actually worked really, really

898
00:48:22,415 --> 00:48:22,615
well.

899
00:48:23,797 --> 00:48:27,458
The other thing we had to do was, uh, then we had stuff for the interface that we'd made

900
00:48:27,478 --> 00:48:32,659
at iPad and Retina resolution, and because that was so big, it would run really, really

901
00:48:32,719 --> 00:48:36,860
slowly on the really slow devices, so then we used the scaler in the opposite direction

902
00:48:37,360 --> 00:48:40,680
to make lower resolution versions of that stuff so it still runs smoothly.

903
00:48:43,241 --> 00:48:45,521
So also, yeah, we changed the name.

904
00:48:46,641 --> 00:48:51,062
We did this at the 11th hour, like, it was the last thing we changed about the game.

905
00:48:51,987 --> 00:48:58,669
And it's not something we took lightly. It was a massive source of stress for both myself and Phil Larson, our marketing manager.

906
00:48:59,010 --> 00:49:02,751
We spent days just being like, oh my god, have we just made the biggest mistake?

907
00:49:02,791 --> 00:49:05,212
Have we just undone all of our long lead marketing?

